Take-home Exercise 2: Applied Spatial Interaction Models: A case study of Singapore public bus commuter flows

Author

Chai Zhixuan

Published

December 6, 2023

Modified

December 12, 2023

1 Overview

In this study, I will continue my geospatial analytics learning journey to demonstrate the potential value of geospatial data science and analysis (GDSA) to integrate publicly available data from multiple sources for building a spatial interaction models to determine factors affecting urban mobility patterns of public bus transit.

2 Getting Started

2.1 Setting the Analytical Tools

The code chunk below installs and loads the various packages

pacman::p_load(tmap, sf, DT, stplanr, sp,
               performance,reshape2,httr,
               ggpubr, tidyverse, corrplot)

A quick check of odbus tibble data frame shows that the values in OROGIN_PT_CODE and DESTINATON_PT_CODE are in numeric data type. Hence, the code chunk below is used to convert these data values into character data type.

odbus$ORIGIN_PT_CODE <- as.factor(odbus$ORIGIN_PT_CODE)
odbus$DESTINATION_PT_CODE <- as.factor(odbus$DESTINATION_PT_CODE)

For the purpose of this exercise, we will extract commuting flows on weekday and between 6 and 9 o’clock. This will mainly be people going to school or work.

odbus6_9 <- odbus %>%
  filter(DAY_TYPE == "WEEKDAY") %>%
  filter(TIME_PER_HOUR >= 6 &
           TIME_PER_HOUR <= 9) %>%
  group_by(ORIGIN_PT_CODE,
           DESTINATION_PT_CODE) %>%
  summarise(TRIPS = sum(TOTAL_TRIPS))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'ORIGIN_PT_CODE'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.

We will save the output in rds format for future used.

write_rds(odbus6_9, "data/rds/odbus6_9.rds")

The code chunk below will be used to import the save odbus6_9.rds into R environment.

odbus6_9 <- read_rds("data/rds/odbus6_9.rds")

3.1.2 Importing Geospatial data into R

For the purpose of this exercise, three geospatial data will be used first. They are:

  • BusStop: This data provides the location of bus stop as at last quarter of 2023.

  • MPSZ-2019: This data provides the sub-zone boundary of URA Master Plan 2019.

  • Hexagon: analytical hexagon data of 375m (this distance is the perpendicular distance between the centre of the hexagon and its edges) to represent the traffic analysis zone (TAZ).

First 2 data sets are in ESRI shapefile format. Last file will be derived from R in the later section 4.2 Creating Hexagon layer.

4 Geospatial data wrangling

4.1 Combining Busstop and mpsz

Code chunk below populates the planning subzone code (i.e. SUBZONE_C) of mpsz sf data frame into busstop sf data frame.

busstop_mpsz <- st_intersection(busstop, mpsz) %>%
  select(BUS_STOP_N, SUBZONE_C) 
Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
all geometries
write_rds(busstop_mpsz, "data/rds/busstop_mpsz.rds")

4.2 Creating Hexagon layer

Now, I am going to create a hexagon layer:

# cell size of layer of 250m
area_honeycomb_grid = st_make_grid(busstop_mpsz, c(750, 750), what = "polygons", square = FALSE, crs = 3414)

6.2 Aspatial

For aspatial, I will be using the following:

  1. HDB: This dataset is used to understand the location of HBD in the hexagon layer
data <- read.csv("data/aspatial/hdb.csv")
coordinates <- data[, c("lng", "lat")]  
spatial_points <- SpatialPointsDataFrame(coordinates, data)

Convert to CRS3414:

# Create a SpatialPoints object
coordinates <- data[, c("lng", "lat")]
spatial_points <- SpatialPoints(coords = coordinates)

# Define the current CRS (WGS84 - EPSG:4326)
proj4string(spatial_points) <- CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")

# Convert SpatialPoints to an sf object
sf_points <- st_as_sf(spatial_points)

# Define EPSG:3414 CRS
epsg_3414_crs <- st_crs(3414)

# Transform the sf object to EPSG:3414
sf_points_3414 <- st_transform(sf_points, crs = epsg_3414_crs)

# Convert back to SpatialPoints
spatial_points_3414 <- as(sf_points_3414, "Spatial")

10 Modelling Results

From the various models, it seems to suggest that the doubly constrained model is the best as it has the lowest RMSE and the best fit plot of MORNING_PEAK against TRIPS.

However, the coefficient of the different variables are removed (indicated as NA). Further investigation is needed to further examine on these findings.

In this aspect, Origin Constraint is the best model to be used (despite a low R2 of 31%).

We observed that the coefficient is the largest for TRAIN_COUNT, followed by SCHOOL_COUNT, BUSINESS_COUNT and HDB_COUNT. All variables are directly related to MORNING_PEAK, and all of the explanatory variables contribute significantly in explaining the MORNING_PEAK as p values are less than 5%.

One reason may be that passengers transit between MRT and buses to commute to work or school, in which the number of passengers who alighted from MRT will affect the number of passengers who are taking buses.

For schools, parents may be bringing their children to school. Business, surprisingly, has a less impact compared to schools, but also accounts for passengers who are going to work between 6am to 9am. One reason may be the concept of working from home where people do not need to head to office daily (link)

HDB_Count is of the least impact as probably passengers may walk a certain distance to another bus stop to take the required bus service to their destination and do not take the bus services which is the nearest to their house.

11 Conclusion

In conclusion, the bus passengers’ volume stands as a pivotal factor affecting the daily lives of students, workers, and various sectors within society. The insights gleaned from existing studies emphasize the critical role of public transportation in ensuring mobility and accessibility for these demographic segments.

Further investigation tailored to the specific needs of students and workers, as well as a granular breakdown across sectors, is imperative. Delving deeper into the nuances of bus passenger volume within these demographics is essential for crafting more efficient and targeted transportation systems. Such focused research endeavors hold the promise of informing strategic policy-making and facilitating the development of transportation infrastructure that better caters to the diverse requirements of students, workers, and the broader society.
